<div class="dablink">For the Welsh courtier and diplomat, see <a href="/wiki/Sir_John_Donne" title="Sir John Donne">Sir John Donne</a>.</div>
<p><b>John Donne</b> (pronounced as <i>dun</i>, <small>IPA</small>: <span title="Pronunciation in IPA" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA_for_English" title="Wikipedia:IPA for English">/dʌn/</a></span>; 1572 – 31 March 1631) was an <a href="/wiki/England" title="England">English</a> <a href="/wiki/Literature_in_English#Jacobean_literature" title="Literature in English" class="mw-redirect">Jacobean</a> poet, preacher and a major representative of the <a href="/wiki/Metaphysical_poets" title="Metaphysical poets">metaphysical poets</a> of the period. His works are notable for their realistic and sensual style and include <a href="/wiki/Sonnet" title="Sonnet">sonnets</a>, love poetry, religious poems, <a href="/wiki/Latin" title="Latin">Latin</a> translations, <a href="/wiki/Epigram" title="Epigram">epigrams</a>, <a href="/wiki/Elegy" title="Elegy">elegies</a>, songs, <a href="/wiki/Satire" title="Satire">satires</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sermon" title="Sermon">sermons</a>. His poetry is noted for its vibrancy of language and inventiveness of <a href="/wiki/Metaphor" title="Metaphor">metaphor</a>, especially as compared to those of his contemporaries.</p>
<p>Despite his great education and poetic talents he lived in <a href="/wiki/Poverty" title="Poverty">poverty</a> for several years, relying heavily on wealthy friends. In 1615 he became an Anglican <a href="/wiki/Priest" title="Priest">priest</a> and, in 1621, was appointed the <a href="/wiki/Dean_of_St_Paul%27s" title="Dean of St Paul's" class="mw-redirect">Dean of St Paul's</a> Cathedral in London. Some scholars believe that Donne's literary works reflect these trends, with <a href="/wiki/Love_poetry" title="Love poetry" class="mw-redirect">love poetry</a> and <a href="/wiki/Satires" title="Satires" class="mw-redirect">satires</a> from his youth and religious <a href="/wiki/Sermons" title="Sermons" class="mw-redirect">sermons</a> during his later years. Other scholars, such as <a href="/wiki/Helen_Gardner_(critic)" title="Helen Gardner (critic)">Helen Gardner</a>, question the validity of this dating since most of his poems were published posthumously (1633). The exception to these is his <i>Anniversaries</i> which were published in 1612 and <i><a href="/wiki/Devotions_upon_Emergent_Occasions" title="Devotions upon Emergent Occasions">Devotions upon Emergent Occasions</a></i> published in 1623. His sermons are also dated, sometimes quite specifically by date and year.</p>
